Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["OptimalBipartiteGraphMatching", "Subsection",
 PageWidth:>WindowWidth,
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4304525161812763`*^9, 3.430452516650445*^9}, {
   3.4304527423882313`*^9, 3.4304527541304283`*^9}, {3.6215335561502047`*^9, 
   3.621533572063485*^9}, {3.6233288112415533`*^9, 3.623328812599122*^9}, 
   3.6233288895042257`*^9, {3.7195743495498996`*^9, 3.719574352301288*^9}, 
   3.726068021125506*^9},ExpressionUUID->"b45eb750-ea32-4883-90a2-\
aeb45d000587"],

Cell["\<\
OptimalBipartiteGraphMatching::usage=
\t\"OptimalBipartiteGraphMatching is SpinDynamica's implementation of the \
Hungarian Algorithm for optimal assignment problems on a bipartite graph. 
Consider the following practical problem: Workers W1, W2, W3 and W4, etc. \
together have to fulfill jobs A, B, C and D, etc. 
Eacher worker ranks his preference with regard to which job he would like to \
perform. 
What is the best assignment of jobs as to maximize the satisfaction of each \
worker? For such cases the Hungarian Algorithm provides an optimal solution. 

In general given a complete weighted Bipartite Graph K(n,n), the Hungarian \
Algorithm provides an optimal solution. 
OptimalBipartiteGraphMatching assumes the Bipartite Graph K(n,n) to be \
arranged into a M(n,n) matrix, 
where columns represent the vertices of the set U and rows the vertices of \
the set V. The matrix-element M_{i,j} is the edge-weight connecting vertices \
i and j.
OptimalBipartiteGraphMatching returns a permutation sequence. Application of \
the permutation sequence to the columns of M leads to a minimization of the \
Trace, 
which is equivalent to an optimal assignment.\";\
\>", "Input",
 PageWidth:>WindowWidth,
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->CompressedData["
1:eJxTTMoPSmViYGCQBGIQ3bzETDY7/aWjwt3lciC6YFLeUsH+l46ZfJybQTTH
